# CHAOS OS // UNIFIED

A gamified, self-contained personal operating system — tasks, study tracking, library,
finances, goals, sleep, weekly review, a calendar, and a level/XP system, all in one
HTML file. Runs entirely in your browser, no backend, no installs.

---

## 🚀 Getting Started (No GitHub Experience Needed)

This gets your own copy of CHAOS OS live on the internet, so you can use it from
any device — phone, tablet, laptop — just by visiting a URL.

### Step 1: Create a GitHub account
1. Go to https://github.com
2. Click **Sign up**, follow the prompts (free).

### Step 2: Create a new repository
1. Once logged in, click the **+** icon (top right) → **New repository**.
2. Name it whatever you like.
3. Set it to **Public**.
4. Click **Create repository**.

### Step 3: Upload the app file
1. On your repo's page, click **Add file** → **Upload files**.
2. Drag in your HTML file — rename it to exactly `index.html`.
3. Scroll down, click **Commit changes**.

### Step 4: Turn on GitHub Pages
1. In your repo, click **Settings** (top menu) → **Pages** (left sidebar).
2. Under "Build and deployment" → Source: **Deploy from a branch**.
3. Branch: **main**, folder: **/ (root)** → **Save**.
4. Wait ~1 minute, refresh the page. A green box shows your live URL, e.g.
   `https://yourusername.github.io/your-repo/`

### Step 5: Open it
Visit that URL on any device. Add it to your phone's home screen for quick access.

---

## ✏️ Updating the App

1. Go to your repo on GitHub → click `index.html`.
2. Click the pencil (✏️) icon, top right.
3. Select all existing text, delete it, paste in the new version.
4. Scroll down, add a short commit message, click **Commit changes**.
5. Wait ~30–60 seconds, revisit your URL. If you don't see the change, hard refresh
   (Ctrl+Shift+R on desktop) or clear cache on mobile.

**Note:** Updating the file only changes the app's code/UI. Your personal data lives
separately in your browser's storage and is untouched by this.

---

## 🔄 Syncing Your Data (Push & Pull via GitHub)

Your data normally only lives in the browser you're using. To carry it between
devices, use the **Sync tab** inside the app.

### One-time setup
1. GitHub → profile picture (top right) → **Settings**.
2. Left sidebar → **Developer settings** → **Personal access tokens** →
   **Tokens (classic)**.
3. **Generate new token** → **Generate new token (classic)**.
4. Name it anything (e.g. `chaos-os`).
5. Under scopes, check only **gist**. Leave everything else unchecked.
6. **Generate token**, copy it immediately (starts with `ghp_...`) — shown only once.
7. In the app's Sync tab, paste it into "GitHub Token" → **Save**.

### Pushing (device → cloud backup)
1. Sync tab → click **↑ PUSH**.
2. First push auto-fills a "Gist ID" on screen — save that ID somewhere (note app,
   screenshot) for use on other devices.

### Pulling (cloud backup → another device)
1. On the new device, open the app's Sync tab.
2. Paste in the same GitHub token → **Save**.
3. Paste in the Gist ID → **Set**.
4. Click **↓ PULL**.

**Heads up:** Pushing overwrites the backup completely. If you edit on two devices
before syncing, whichever pushes *last* wins — the other device's unsynced changes
get overwritten.

---

## 📅 Syncing with Google Calendar

Push events from the app's Calendar tab into your real Google Calendar, and pull
your Google Calendar events back into the app.

### One-time setup
1. Go to https://console.cloud.google.com, sign in.
2. Project dropdown → **New Project** → name it anything → **Create**. Select it
   once created.
3. Search bar → **Google Calendar API** → click it → **Enable**.
4. Left sidebar → **APIs & Services** → **OAuth consent screen**.
   - User type: **External** → **Create**.
   - Fill in app name + your email → click through remaining steps with defaults.
5. Same consent screen → scroll to **Test users** → **+ Add users** → add your own
   Gmail address → **Save**. (Required, or Google blocks your own sign-in.)
6. Left sidebar → **Credentials** → **Create Credentials** → **OAuth client ID**.
   - Application type: **Web application**.
   - Under "Authorized JavaScript origins" → **+ Add URI** → enter your site's
     domain only, no path, no trailing slash:
     `https://yourusername.github.io`
   - **Create**.
7. Copy the **Client ID** (ends in `.apps.googleusercontent.com`).
8. In the app's Calendar tab, paste it into "OAUTH CLIENT ID" → **Save**.

### Using it
- **Connect**: Calendar tab → **🔗 Connect** → pick your Google account → approve.
- **Push**: add events by clicking a day on the calendar grid, then **↑ Push Events**.
- **Pull**: click **↓ Pull Events** to bring in real Google Calendar events
  (roughly past month → next 6 months), tagged with a small "G".

**Heads up:** You'll need to click Connect again each new browser session — only
the Client ID is remembered, not the connection itself, for security.

---

## 🔐 Is This Safe? (Public Repo + Personal Data)

Short answer: yes, with one nuance worth understanding.

**Things that are fine to be public** (and already are, in your repo/README):
- The **GitHub Pages URL** itself — it's just an empty app shell with zero personal
  data baked in. Anyone visiting gets a blank instance.
- The **Google OAuth Client ID** — this is *designed* to be public, the same way
  every "Sign in with Google" button on the internet exposes its Client ID. It only
  identifies which app is asking, it can't grant access by itself. Google also
  locks it to your exact registered origin and (while in Testing mode) to your
  specific Test User account.

**Things that must stay private** (never put these in the repo/README):
- Your **GitHub Personal Access Token** — only ever paste this into the app's Sync
  tab fields at runtime, never hardcode it into the HTML file.
- Your **Gist ID** — not secret-secret, but don't share it publicly; anyone with
  the exact ID/URL can view that Gist's raw contents (it's "unlisted," not
  encrypted or access-controlled).

**Where your actual data lives:**
- **Default**: only in your browser's local storage, on your device, never
  transmitted anywhere.
- **After Push**: a full JSON snapshot of everything (tasks, money, sleep, mood
  journal, etc.) sits as plaintext in a GitHub Gist tied to your account. Not
  indexed/searchable, but not encrypted — readable by anyone who gets the exact
  link, or technically by GitHub under their own access policies.
- **Google Calendar sync**: events live in your normal Google Calendar, under
  your account's standard security.

**Practical takeaway:** for tasks, study logs, money, sleep — this setup is fine,
low risk, exactly what it's built for. For anything more personal (e.g. mood
journal entries), be aware the Gist backup isn't truly private, just obscure. If
that matters to you, a passphrase-encryption layer can be added so the Gist stores
unreadable ciphertext instead of plain text — ask if you want this built in.

